                <h2>PRP Injection vs Cortisone Injection</h2>
                <p>Cortisone (corticosteroid) injections have been used for decades to manage pain and inflammation, particularly in joints. While effective for short-term relief, they work very differently from PRP:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Cortisone suppresses inflammation and masks pain. PRP stimulates actual tissue repair and regeneration. Cortisone treats the symptom; PRP addresses the underlying cause.</li>
                    <li><strong>Duration of Relief:</strong> Cortisone provides relief for a few weeks to a few months. PRP results can last 6-18 months and improve over time as tissue heals.</li>
                    <li><strong>Long-Term Effects:</strong> Repeated cortisone injections can weaken tendons, thin cartilage, and damage surrounding tissue over time. PRP strengthens and rebuilds tissue with no degenerative side effects.</li>
                    <li><strong>Number of Injections:</strong> Doctors typically limit cortisone injections to 3-4 per year per joint due to tissue damage risks. PRP has no such limitation because it heals rather than harms.</li>
                    <li><strong>Source:</strong> Cortisone is a synthetic steroid. PRP comes from your own blood, making it completely natural and biocompatible.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>For acute inflammation or severe pain that needs immediate relief, cortisone may be appropriate as a short-term solution. But for long-term healing and tissue regeneration, PRP is the superior choice. Many patients who have relied on cortisone injections for years are now switching to PRP for more sustainable results.</p>

                <h2>PRP Injection vs Dermal Fillers</h2>
                <p>In the context of facial rejuvenation, PRP injections and dermal fillers serve different purposes and work in fundamentally different ways:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Composition:</strong> Dermal fillers are made of synthetic or semi-synthetic materials like hyaluronic acid, calcium hydroxylapatite, or poly-L-lactic acid. PRP is made entirely from your own blood.</li>
                    <li><strong>How They Work:</strong> Fillers physically add volume beneath the skin to fill wrinkles and plump up areas like the cheeks and lips. PRP stimulates your body to produce its own collagen and elastin, improving skin quality from within.</li>
                    <li><strong>Results:</strong> Fillers provide instant visible results that last 6-18 months depending on the product. PRP results develop gradually over 2-3 months as collagen builds up, and can last 12 months or longer with maintenance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Natural Appearance:</strong> PRP produces very natural-looking results because it enhances your own skin rather than adding foreign material. Fillers, when done well, look natural too, but there is always a slight risk of an overdone appearance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Side Effects:</strong> Fillers can cause lumps, migration, or vascular occlusion in rare cases. PRP side effects are limited to temporary redness and mild swelling since it is your own plasma.</li>
                    <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Fillers are ideal for adding volume and treating deep wrinkles or hollow areas. PRP is ideal for overall skin quality improvement, fine lines, texture, and a natural glow.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Many clinics, including DenceSpot, recommend combining PRP with dermal fillers for comprehensive facial rejuvenation. The fillers provide immediate structural improvement while PRP works in the background to improve skin quality over time. This combination approach delivers both instant and long-lasting results.</p>

